One of the best lessons I learned from my grandmother was the fact that we can appreciate other peoples gifts and abilities without it diminishing who we are.

I always try to remember this as the temptation to compare creeps in.

A few things I learned over our weekend family trip. 

1. I am not a Disney mom. I enjoy ONE day at the park every few years or so and that’s it for me. (If you LOVE Disney, I admire your strength and extreme patience😆. )

2. When I do go back to Disneyland, I am bringing my own Diet Dr. Pepper.

3. The birria tacos in California Adventure are delicious.

4. Hotels for larger families are hard to find but due to a cancelled flight we ended up at a Staybridge Suites that was comfortable and clean with 2 bedrooms and a kitchen for a decent price! 

5. Trips with the family are equal parts fun and frustrating but totally worth it.

A little habit I have been really loving that started like this:

As I punched in 90 seconds on the microwave I began to wonder how much I could get done before the timer went off.

I went to work and was so surprised to find that I could empty the whole dishwasher in that time. 

I sat down with my Perk feeling pretty great about what I had gotten done and the habit has stuck.

Try this one out (if you haven’t already ) especially if you, like me, are a little competitive and need a little motivation to clean.
Works like a charm🙌.

I don’t know about you but sometimes the screen time battle feels exhausting. It’s tempting to just give up. 
Accept it.
Chalk it all up to “it’s just how things are now”.

But then I take a step back and realize that I can’t. 
I can’t do that to my kids- even though they wish I would.

So to anyone feeling this weight and are wondering if it’s worth it, here are just 3 very watered down reasons why I am not giving up.

And just to be clear. We do screens.

The battle for our family is to not let them take over. We are just striving for balance.

Who is with me? 

#screentime #standuptoscreens
#parenting

Have you seen this analogy before? It’s a classic.

Rocks( or random assortment of balls)= Highest priorities: family time, spirituality, work, learning, helping. Etc.
Pebbles( or smaller whatevers)= friends, hobbies, sports, reading, creating 
Sand (or sugar)= consumption leisure activities; tv, movies, scrolling, video games, etc. 

When our kids ask for screen time we ask them if they have done their “rocks” first and usually the answer is no🤣.

We added another layer as well because I didn’t want my kids speeding through the most important things to get to the “sand” which I will share in my stories. 

#screentime #parenting #priorities

I had a aha moment when chatting with one of my boys as to why they couldn’t watch tv until their “rocks” were done.

This is far bigger than just screens. It’s about self mastery.
It’s the real challenge of our time.

I love this thought by James Allen, author of As a Man Thinketh:

“In all human affairs there are efforts and there are results, and the strength of the effort is the measure of the result. Chance is not. “Gifts”, powers, material, intellectual and spiritual possessions are the fruit of effort;they are thoughts completed, objects accomplished, visions realized.”

That is the opportunity I want my kids to have. To have time and space to put effort into what matters most.

We can do this!! 

#screentime #selfmastery #kids

How far would you go to make sure you could go on a trip?

In case you missed my stories last week we figured out the answer to that question… and the answer was Houston.

Due to the passport processing delays, we realized a few days ago that we would not get two of our kids passports in time for our trip that we are leaving on tomorrow.

I started preparing my brain to stay behind with the kids without passports but knew I would be so sad to miss out… and Jace would be too.

So Thursday morning we made a call and found out that we could get a passport same day… in Houston.

Within minutes I made flights and we left 3 hours later.

It felt a little crazy but we walked out with passports and felt so happy about it… it almost made up for being so frustrated that we had to go there in the first place. 

We ended our 8 hour day at the federal building with some good Texas BBQ and headed back home.

These two boys were amazing sports the whole time. 

And now we all get to go on our trip together! 

#tmtravels

If you are feeling resentful or overwhelmed by the mental load of motherhood, it is so important to realize that you don’t actually have to do any of the things you are doing.

OR
2. You realize you can ask for help/delegate 
OR
3. You realize you can let it go.

Give it a try and see what happens.❤️

It’s fairly easy for me to talk about Jesus; who he was, what he did and why it matters. It’s not very hard for me to believe in him.
But what feels harder is to believe that He did what he did EVEN FOR ME. 

Maybe it feels like your challenges are too impossible… or maybe on the other end- too insignificant.

Maybe it feels like your weaknesses aren’t worth his time or trouble. There are surely others who need him more.

Sometimes that’s what I am thinking, without even realizing it.

But this weekend I felt a little nudge that, yes He did what He did EVEN FOR ME and believing that truth is life changing. 

“There is no physical pain, no anguish of soul, no suffering of spirit, no infirmity or weakness that you or I ever experience during our mortal journey that the Savior did not experience first. You and I in a moment of weakness may cry out, “No one understands. No one knows.” No human being, perhaps, knows. But the Son of God perfectly knows and understands, for He felt and bore our burdens before we ever did. “

-Elder Bednar “In the Strength of the Lord”.

Last week we fulfilled a dream of mine to take our kids to Europe.

I never expected to take a toddler with us🤣, but after I found an amazing deal on @flightsfromhome and feeling the time that we have our oldest living at home running short, we decided to go for it.

I wish I could say this trip was an absolute dream come true, but in reality it was a little rocky.

Mistakes were made and learned from (I will share those!) and I felt disappointed that I felt disappointed in how it all went.

However, as I look through our photos, I realized that there were so many wonderful, amazing unforgettable (in all of the ways) moments and despite at all, I am grateful we got to go experience as a family!

The kids were SO great ( minus the fighting in the car, which happens anywhere) and I am so proud of the way they handled the stress and chaos that sometimes was felt. They also were so encouraging and cheered me up when I felt discouraged.
They are incredible little people. 

Even Dane was amazing. Including the flight! #dreambaby

 I guess the moral of the story is that there is always good if you look for it. 
Even on crazy trips with kids🤣

#tmfamily

Not included on this list but should also get honorable mention is lots of sunshine and cold diet DP. 

Anything else you would add? 

#tmsummer

Here is how the big five work in our home;

All of five of these things need to be done before screen time in the summer. That’s it! 
*we also have a designated screen time so the kids don’t get up at 5am to rush through these things to have a full day of screens🤣😉.)

They can can any five things that matter to you- it can even be 2, 3 or 4- whatever fits your family the best.
If you want to implement the big 5 in your family this summer just take a minute to think about what you want then to be. Talk through it with your kids and give support in coming up with what they might want to practice/learn or create.

Would love to know if you have done something similar.

You want your kids to be on board with your summer plans?
The best way to do this is have a family summer planning meeting.
Get their suggestions and let them make choices whenever possible. 
Especially as kids get older, the more control they feel they have, the more willing they are to go along with things.
This could look like letting everyone choose an activity during the week or letting them sign up for jobs instead of just being assigned.
You, the parent are still in charge but kids do appreciate being a part of the process. 

#summerplanning #summer #familymeetings

Every summer we do what we call the BIG FIVE. 
These are five things that my kids do before screen time/friend time in the summer. 
Here are a few ideas, but you can totally make this your own by including what matters most to you.

Next time you hear “this isn’t fun” or “I am bored” think this: I am creating space for my child to experience joy.

I love this statement from the book GiST: the essence of raising life ready kids:

“Fun is fleeting and momentary in nature. It is a wonderful seasoning for life, but not the whole meal. Joy, on the other hand is far more enduring. It doesn’t show up as easily as fun but it reminds us that life is worthwhile in a way that fun doesn’t. 
There is not much fun in being honest, or in hard work, and little fun at all in self-discipline. What fun is there in being kind, a good sibling or a person of your word. What is fun about being grateful for what you have or sacrificing for someone with less.
Joy usually costs a little more and lasts a little longer, and will give experiences that a focus on fun will never produce.”

Fun is good, joy us better.
You are doing great things out there ladies❤️

#summer

My 13 year old made me a BeReal account! 🤣
I decided to give it a try to check out how I would feel about my kids being on it.
Overall it’s a pretty good attempt at changing the things that aren’t great about social media. 
But it’s still something that can distract a pull kids away from what’s amazing about being a kid.

Out of any of the options available BeReal seems to be a good starting place for high school kids who are ready and want to connect with friends in a safer* social media environment. 
*guidance and supervision still needed. 
I am not a fan of any of the other options out there right now as I am fiercely protective of my kids in this digital space(if you haven’t noticed). 
Any younger than that I don’t feel is necessary to be on an app like this…but my kids don’t get smart phones until high school anyway so it’s not even an option🤷‍♀️.
That’s my 2 cents and hope it helps!

When I started doing this, it changed the whole morning. 

I used to get bothered when my kids would wake up in the morning- especially if it interrupted my routine.
But then I started thinking about how crummy that must feel to wake up to a mom who didn’t seem happy to see them.
I could see how it impacted how they felt not just about me- but about themselves.

So I started to make a deliberate effort to be happy to see them every morning.
It only takes a minute or two and it really makes a huge difference.

As a person who uses her phone for work as well as just scrolling, this is something that I have to be extra deliberate about.

And while most of them time I am being productive while on my phone- my kids don’t know that.
So if I am on my phone when my kids need me, I try to put it down and look them in the eye.
The message it sends is that “ you matter to me”- which is really what every kid really wants to know.

This one is something that I am really working hard on.
I started noticing that when I had a lot going on it was feeling worn down, I would say “what” in a very annoyed way when my kids would say my name.

A few of them would look down and say “nevermind”… because they could sense how I was feeling. 
I felt so bad that I was completely shutting them down.

I decided then and there that I would work on the skill of saying “what” more pleasant… or at least keep it neutral🤣. 

Just because I am feeling annoyed doesn’t mean I need to talk like it.

So, I am working on it.
A little shift that can make a big difference.

Yesterday my 5th grader interviewed me for his school report about 9/11.
It made me feel a little old to be reminiscing about this part of our countries history- but it’s where I am in life😉🤣. 
He asked me questions like - where was I? How did I feel? What was it like?

But the question that took me off gaurd was this:

What do you want me to know and remember about 9/11? 

I thought for a minute- and then got a little emotional and said this:

The people who did what they did hated America and wanted to destroy us.
But they didn’t.
So I want you to remember that- they didn’t.
People came together and people helped and we got stronger. Because that’s what we do in America.

And while the unity that we felt then feels so far gone- I still believe it’s there deep down.

Hopefully it’s part of what we remember because when we remember- we can get back there.

I will tell you what I have concluded. 
It’s the control. Or lack of it. For the most part. 
I didn’t realize how much I was able to control about my kids daily lives before they were teens.

I controlled their schedules, what and when they ate, bedtimes, play dates, activities, books they read… and then one day- you can’t.

And that feels really hard and really scary.

But it’s supposed to happen this way.
We want our teens to become independent and prepare to leave the nest.

So, if you are like me and feel a little terrified about the shift… get out all your feelings while scrubbing your counter and then loosen that grip just a little bit ❤️.
It’s all going to be OK.

So many people think that to overcome negative thinking, we just have to stop thinking so negatively. 
But it’s not that easy- as you probably know. That rarely works because the reality is our brain NEEDS to have thoughts.
So if you want to break out of a cycle of negative thinking, you have to retrain your brain to default to a different thought.
And because our brains sometimes resist that positive thought- it is easier to make changes simply with thoughts that aren’t negative.
I am talking more about it in my stories today and giving 2 tips that help me with this.

Negative consequences could look like:

Sibling fighting during the holiday season sometimes feels worse than just everyday sibling fighting, right?! 
If this is feels true for you, try this: 

Pay attention to what you are making their fighting mean.
When we pour our heart and soul into creating fun or special moments for our kids, it is easy to take the fighting personally.
Like they are doing it TO YOU. To ruin everything.
Which makes us feel so angry and hurt and resentful.

What is more true is that their fighting has nothing to do with you. 
Believing this helps us to have a little more patience to endure that fight and more presence of mind to help them work through it if needed. 

Hope it helps make the holidays a little easier❤️

If you are feeling worried that your kids are too ungrateful or care too much about getting presents, this is for you.
3 things to tell yourself so you can feel less worried… because there is a really good chance that your kids will turn out to be caring, giving adults- just like you are❤️.

5 Ways to Serve as a Family:

1. Free Activities at Home
* Writing Notes of Kindness: Sending heartfelt messages to neighbors’ costs nothing but time and effort, leaving a lasting impact.
* Adopting a Grandparent: Visiting elderly neighbors or seniors in local communities is such a happy way to serve.

2. Free Community Engagement
* Volunteering at St. Vincent’s Dining Hall: Participating in meal service for those in need fosters empathy and gratitude. Visit their website for more information.

3. Low-Cost Community Involvement
* Sacrificial Giving: Teaching children the concept of sacrifice by forgoing eating out using those funds to someone in need.
* Participating in ‘A Babe is Born’ Event: Supporting refugee families through Christmas-themed events. Visit their social page to learn more.

4. Community Service with Costs
* Contributing to Ronald McDonald House: Preparing and serving meals for families in need, providing support and comfort. Learn more on their website.

5. Close-to-Home Initiatives
* Hosting a Hot Chocolate Stand: Creating a free hot chocolate station in the neighborhood fosters a sense of community.
* Operation Christmas Child: Filling shoeboxes with gifts for children in need and dropping them off at designated centers. Learn more on their website.

Will it be an earlier bed time or a nap for you? 

I know sleep can be so challenging when kids keep life unpredictable.  At this stage in our lives we might not be able to count on a solid eight hours of sleep, but aiming to go to sleep a little earlier or plan for a quick restorative nap in the day can do a lot of good. 

Let’s do this🙌.
